for the well-being of adults and children. With a lens toward socioeconomic inequality and racial-ethnic variation in family patterns, Families in America illustrates how family diversity is now the norm. The Sociology in the Twenty-First Century series introduces students to a range of sociological issues of broad interest in the United States today, with each volume addressing topics such as family, race, immigration, gender, education, and social inequality. These books—intended for classroom use—will highlight findings from current, rigorous research and demographic data while including stories about people’s experiences to illustrate major themes in an accessible manner. Learn more at www.ucpress.edu/go/sociologyinthe21stcentury.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFamilies - United States. 0aFamilieszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  a21st century families.  aamerican family.  acontemporary families.  adomestic policy.  afamilies in america.  afamily formation.  afamily.  agender studies.  ahistory of the family.  amarriage and divorce in america.  amarriage family.  amarriage policy.  arepartnering.  asame sex marriage.  asocial inequality.  asocial science.  asocioeconomic inequality in the us.  asociological issues.  asociology.  atraditional families.  atraditional marriage.  awelfare reform.  awork family issues.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052028588040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096124140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961241/original  a978-3-11-0